As a holiday gift to Boston Globe readers who are interested in "hopping 
on the Internet and checking it out" but may not know where to start, 
the editor of the Globe's VOXBOX section asked me to put together a 
quick "how to do it, where to start, whom to call" piece that also 
suggests things to do which may also be news to existing "Internauts." 

On the one hand, this -- like many Internet-related questions -- doesn't 
have an answer that's short, simple, helpful and still short.  

Especially short.  When I tackled this question in the Internet book I 
wrote, _The Internet Guide for New Users_ (McGraw-Hill, 1993), Chapter 
2: "The Internet on a Dollar A Day: How to Get a User Account and Plug 
In" ran forty book pages, and the whole book's 600+ pages. 

On the other hand, as you'll see, it IS possible to give a short yet 
useful answer -- by narrowing the question down sufficiently, and not 
attempting to give an answer to comprehensive as to overwhelm the reader 
with more information and choices than they handle. 

This article therefore:

o Is targetted especially at people in the Boston Globe's primary 
  circulation areas -- the greater Boston area and the rest of 
  Massachusetts, and portions of New Hampshire and Rhode Island. 

o Assumes you'll get a "net buddy" to help you with the less familiar 
  parts

o Assumes you'll have access to one or more Internet "navigators" --
  in particular, Gopher -- which will make your efforts much easier.


