This article talks about how to access the Internet for individuals, at 
home or the office, by obtaining an individual account, using a personal 
computer and modem, and connecting via your telephone.  (It's also 
possible to connect your office computers and networks up directly to 
the Internet, but that's outside the scope of this piece.) 

If you're serious about being an Internet user for personal or 
professional activities, you'll probably want to invest some time and 
money getting up to speed -- buy one or more Internet books (I wrote one 
-- and there are numerous others), take a course from the Boston 
Computer Society or elsewhere, etc.  

But is is possible for even a complete newcomer who's never taken 
keyboard or mouse in hand to get onto the Internet and begin exploring 
its virtual nooks and cyber-byways.  

Once on, you can send e-mail to the Boston Globe, read and follow 
topical discussions, retrieve documents and programs, play multi-user 
games, and do all sorts of other nifty stuff!  As you'll see in the 
second half of this article, there's no shortage of things you can do 
on/with the Internet that are easy yet immediately rewarding.  You don't 
have to become a heavy-duty computer expert! 


