A FEW CAUTIONARY WORDS

One quick caution: The "things to do" in this article primarily involve 
finding and retrieving information from the Internet, rather than 
interacting with other people or putting your own thoughts and 
information onto the Internet. 

As a newcomer (a.k.a. "newbie"), it is best to start by being a 
background participant -- a "lurker."  There's nothing wrong with this 
-- just because you read the Globe every day doesn't mean you have to 
write a Letter to the Editor daily. 

The Internet is used by a multitude of communities around the country 
and world -- tens of millions of people, encompassing many different 
cultures, plus the Internet and on-line world has a very strong culture 
of its own.  It's easy to waste resources or annoy lots of people 
deliberately and even by accident.  

If you plan to be a long-time resident of cyberspace, plan to learn and 
follow its rules and guidelines.  Here's the short version:

o Remember that anything you do or say in the Internet's "public places" 
  may be read by your family, friends, and boss -- don't say anything you 
  aren't "willing to see on the front page of tomorrow's Boston Globe." 

o Don't post a message to a mailing list or Usenet Newsgroup until 
  you've been reading it for AT LEAST two weeks.  This will help you
  avoid many common beginner errors (you'll get to watch other people 
  make them, and see what response they get).

OK, buckle up your virtual seat belt and let's go!  In the first half, 
let's see how to get access to the Internet, then in the second half 
we'll explore some interesting, easy-to-use parts of the Internet. 


STEP 1: Get Yourself a "Net Buddy" (The "Net Buddy System") 

For your initial forays into the Internet, your best resource is a "net 
buddy" -- someone (or several people) who's already using the Internet 
and who's willing to help you muddle through the early stages of gaining 
access and learning to "work the controls."  Ask around.  

If you can't find an Internet-familiar friend, try for someone who's 
familiar with CompuServe, MCI Mail, Prodigy or a BBS (Bulletin Board 
System) -- they should be able to help you with the "getting connected" 
parts if nothing else. 

Your "net buddy" may be a co-worker, a friend, the Boston Computer 
Society's Internet SIG (Special Interest Group)... you're looking for a 
resource that can help you with answers and tips especially during those 
first sessions when you may not be able to identify and articulate your 
real problems and questions.  

Suggestions: If possible, pick someone who's not a long-distance call 
away; even better, someone who can sit next to you for at least your 
first one or two sessions. 

The odds are good that within a startlingly short time you'll be ready 
to be someone else's "net buddy." 


STEP 2: Get Computer, Modem, and Phone.

If you don't already have the necessary equipment to "go on-line," it's 
time to buy, rent or borrow it.  (You're bound to know one or more 
people who can help you do this.)  

You don't need fancy or expensive equipment; someone's obsolete computer 
that they feel is completely worthless may be adequate, or you may find 
a used machine for $100 or less! 

You'll need a COMPUTER -- almost any personal computer will do, such as 
a PC-compatible running DOS or Windows, any Apple computer, Amiga, etc. 
-- as long as it can run a COMMUNICATIONS PROGRAM, such as ProComm, 
MicroPhone, and support a MODEM. 

In fact, you'll also need a communications program.  Look for one that 
supports "VT100 terminal emulation."  (Most do.)  Inexpensive and free 
communications programs are readily available.  You also may already 
have one --for example, Microsoft Windows and many of today's computer 
systems include this.  Most modems also include a free comm program, 
although you may decide you want a different one.  

You'll need to know how to turn this program on, set it so it talks to 
the appropriate COMMUNICATIONS PORT (e.g., COMM1, COMM2) on your 
computer, how to load in telephone numbers and a few pieces of 
information for each.  

In particular, you'll want to learn how to set SPEED (usually in bits 
per second or baud), # of DATA BITS, STOP BIT, and PARITY BIT.  For 
example: ST&D World, 617-730-WRLD, 9600 bps, 8 bits data, Stop 1, Parity 
None.  

At some point, you'll probably also want to learn how to "capture" text 
from your screen to a file on your computer's hard drive, and how to 
upload/download files between your computer and your Internet account.  
(It's not hard to do, but how to do it with your computer isn't always 
obvious.) 

You'll need a MODEM.  Even a 1,200 or 2400 baud modem can suffice; these 
are available for as little as $40 these days.  However, if you're 
serious about being online, you'll want one that can handle speeds of 
9,600 or even 14,400 bits per second (bps); otherwise things may appear 
slowwww.  You can get a modem like this for under $200. 

You'll also need a phone line you can use, and the appropriate wires to 
connect up.  (If you have Call-Waiting service, remember to first dial 
*70 before the actual phone number; this disables (turns off) Call-
Waiting until you hang up again.) 

You may find yourself instantly successful at using the Internet, 
especially if you've used a BBS or on-line service before.  If you 
haven't, be ready to spend a few hours getting the hang of simply 
connecting and learning how to enter commands to your account.  It's not 
that expensive -- not counting the cost of phone message units, 
connecting should only be costing you one to three dollars per hour.  
And, as noted elsewhere, many services give you the first hour or 
several hours free! 


STEP 3: Get an "Internet Account."

The easiest, cheapest, quickest way to gain access to the Internet is to 
get an account with an online service or BBS that offers "Internet 
access." 

As part of your account, you'll get a "net ID" includes your "user-
name," such as "john.smith" plus a "site name" like "world.std.com" -- 
these get put together like so "john.smith@world.std.com" to form your 
INTERNET E-MAIL ADDRESS.  You'll also get a password, which you should 
write down someplace safe (not under your keyboard!) and be sure to 
remember. 

The greater Boston area is blessed with many Internet account providers.  
Most charge around $1-$3/hour.  Free trial periods of one to five hours 
are common.  There are also many offering no-charge or donation access, 
and organization-based services available for free to their members -- 
one downside may be frequent busy signals or poorer support for users. 
 
The section "Get Your Starter Internet Access Here" at the end of this 
article offers contact info for some of the leading Boston-area Internet 
access providers.  (Be sure to inquire about additional modem numbers in 
your local calling area.)  If you've got Gopher access, you can also 
look for the Internet Account Providers area I've set up in the "Dern's 
Internet Info, News and Views" gopherspace at internet.com. 


Base your choice on factors such as: 

o being within your local phone calling area (to keep your phone 
  bill down) 

o User interface and local on-line help.  Don't expect a Graphic User 
  Interface like AOL or Prodigy here; you'll get simple menuing systems, 
  or perhaps just a Unix prompt (analogous to the DOS "C:>" prompt.  
  Many new users like DELPHI's enhanced menus. 

If you're already familiar with Unix, you may prefer to go straight to 
World.  In any case, standard Internet facilities like Gopher quickly 
present you with a more informative, easy to use window to the Internet. 

All full-service Internet access providers should offer comparable sets 
of service: electronic mail, access to the Usenet "bulletin board" 
Newsgroups, the ability to retrieve and download files, real-time 
Internet "Chat," navigators like Gopher and WorldWideWeb, etc. 

If you already have an account on an online service like America OnLine, 
CompuServe, GEnie, or Prodigy, you have limited access to the Internet 
via electronic mail; however, this is like seeing Star Wars with a paper 
bag over your head - far from the real experience. 

Don't worry too much about "making the right choice."  Once you're "on 
the net" you can easily locate lists and information of other providers; 
changing or getting another account is very easy.  You'll learn how in 
the second half.  (But don't make up new business cards with your "net 
address" until you're certain.)  


STEP 4: Log in and hop on.

Now that you've got the equipment and an account, it's time to 
stick a toe into cyberspace.  
    
You'll do this by typing some short commands as given below, or 
possibly using your mouse to select menu items or icons.  Here's 
a few quick tips:

o <RETURN> means the key labelled <RETURN> or <ENTER> on your keyboard.  
  <CONTROL-character>, also often given as ^char, means holding down the 
  <CONTROL> key and the indicated character simultaneously, such 
  <CONTROL-C> (a.k.a. CTRL-C or ^C), <CONTROL-D>, etc.  

o Other keys you're likely to use include "?" or "h" for on-line help, 
  <SPACE> (the 'space' bar'), and the four "arrow-keys" (up, down, right 
  and left). 

o Unlike DOS, many things in the Internet are "case sensitive" -- for 
  example, README, ReadMe, and readme would be the names of three 
  different files.  "Punctuation" counts -- pay attention to spaces 
  (don't add or leave them out), etc. 

o :-) is a "smiley-face" and means "just kidding" or "meant humorously.  
  Tilt your head to the left and look at it again -- see the "smile"? 

o "FAQ" refers to a compilation of Frequently-Asked Questions, and their 
  answers.  There's one or more FAQ documents for most major Internet 
  services and activities, and for most Usenet Newsgroups.  When in 
  doubt, before asking someone, find and read the appropriate FAQ. 

o If all else fails, hang up the phone and a) start again or b) contact 
  your Net Buddy for help. 


Start by dialing up.  (You may want your Net Buddy here for the first 
try.) 

1. Power up your computer and modem 
2. Make sure the modem is connected to the phone line 
3. Select your communications program 
4. Select the Internet entry to be dialed.  You'll hear some whistling 
   and windy sounds; after a few seconds, you should see text on your 
   screen.  (If the sound stops but no text appears, try hitting the 
   <RETURN> key a few times.) 
5. When you see something like "login:" or "user-ID:", type your 
   username followed by the <RETURN> key. 
6. When you see something like "Password:" type in your password 
   followed by the <RETURN> key.  (You won't see your password on the 
   screen when you type it.  This is a security feature.) 
7. If you see a prompt like "Terminal?" or (term=vt100)?, enter 
   <RETURN>; if you are asked for a terminal type, type 
   "vt100 <RETURN>".  Get your net buddy to help you through this stuff. 

Eventually you'll get a "system prompt," such as "world%" or simply "%" 
or "$". 
 

HEIGH HO, TO CYBERSPACE WE GO

You've now learned how to get up and running on the Internet -- find a 
"net buddy" to help you cut through the fog, set up a PC and modem, get 
an Internet user account and log in.  At this point, you are hopefully 
able to access the Internet, and can start giving commands that let you 
use and explore the Internet.  (If not, keep reading anyway to get a 
sense of what you can do "once you get there.")

Once you're on the Internet, there are a thousand and one things you can 
do -- and many of them are interesting.  Now that you're up and running 
on the Internet, here's a few easy Internet activities you can do, 
ranging from holiday-related and contacting the Boston Globe to browsing 
for books and getting an I-Ching reading.  Enjoy! 


