* TRY THIS: Get the FAQs

FAQs -- Frequently Asked Questions and their Answers documents -- for 
most aspects of the Internet and Usenet are readily available for 
reading and retrieval from a number of Internet sources, including: 

o in the Usenet news.answers Newsgroup; also, each Newsgroup's FAQ can 
  usually be found in that Newsgroup 

o from many Gopher menus 

o by anonymous-FTP file transfer from the site  rtfm.mit.edu enter  "ftp 
  rtfm.mit.edu <RETURN>"  (or "ncftp" if it's available) 

Ask your Net Buddy for help here.



* TRY THIS: Check out the discussions of your favorite movies and TV 
  series, games, hobbies, etc. 

The Usenet is the Internet-based global "BBS" -- bulletin board system -
- of over five thousand topical discussion areas, or Newsgroups.  Many 
are serious technical and business forums, but there are also hundreds 
for hobby, social and personal interests.  Many Internet sites also 
carry popular newspaper columnists like Mike Royko, Ms. Manners and Dave 
Barry. 

You access Usenet Newsgroups via a "newsreader" program.  Popular ones 
on dial-up Internet sites include "trn" "nn" and "tin"; like Gopher, you 
can do most basic selection and reading activities with little more than 
the <SPACE>, <RETURN>, and arrow keys, plus "?" or "h" for online help. 

Like joining any new "club," it's strongly recommended you start by 
READING the postings in a given Usenet group for at least two weeks 
before attempting to pose a question or contribute an answer.  

Get your "net buddy" to identify and select five or ten Newsgroups of 
possible interest, and to help you set things up so you can read them.  
If you know the name of a Newsgroup you want to read, you can also 
access it by giving the name of your newsreader and the newsgroup, e.g. 

    trn news.announce.newusers <RETURN>


* TRY THIS: Find recipes and other information with keyword searches 

The Internet's WAIS (Wide Area Information Server) facility lets you do 
keyword searches through collections of text information such as recipe 
collections, the online file of Hacker's jargon, and hundreds of other 
serious and light-heartded sources. 

If you can't access WAIS through an entry in a Gopher or other menu 
(e.g., one like "Gopher and other Internet servers"), enter 

    telnet quake.think.com <RETURN>

and enter "swais" in response to the "login" prompt.  Try giving 
"recipes" or "jargon" as a starting keyword to select a WAIS database; 
use the <SPACE>, <ENTER>, arrow, and "?" keys to do basic navigation. 


